{"id":"1707.09556","submitter":"Ferdinand Ihringer","authors":"Ferdinand Ihringer, Deepak Rajendraprasad, Thilo V. Weinert","title":"New bounds on the Ramsey number $r(I_m, L_n)$","comments":"20 pages, incorporated many reviewer's comments","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the Ramsey numbers $r(I_m, L_n)$ which is the minimal natural\nnumber $k$ such that every oriented graph on $k$ vertices contains either an\nindependent set of size $m$ or a transitive tournament on $n$ vertices. Apart\nfrom the finitary combinatorial interest, these Ramsey numbers are of interest\nto set theorists since it is known that $r(\\omega m, n) = \\omega r(I_m, L_n)$,\nwhere $\\omega$ is the lowest transfinite ordinal number, and $r(\\kappa m, n) =\n\\kappa r(I_m, L_n)$ for all initial ordinals $\\kappa$. Continuing the research\nby Bermond from 1974 who did show $r(I_3, L_3) = 9$, we prove $r(I_4, L_3) =\n15$ and $r(I_5, L_3) = 23$. The upper bounds for both the estimates above are\nobtained by improving the upper bound of $m^2$ on $r(I_m, L_3)$ due to Larson\nand Mitchell (1997) to $m^2 - m + 3$. Additionally, we provide asymptotic upper\nbounds on $r(I_m, L_n)$ for all $n \\geq 3$. In particular, we show that $r(I_m,\nL_3) \\in \\Theta(m^2 / \\log m)$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 29 Jul 2017 21:01:27 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 30 Apr 2018 11:26:36 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 8 Apr 2020 09:39:26 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-04-09"}
